  "prompt": "What should you do if you eat undercooked chicken?",
  "response": "If you\u2019ve eaten undercooked chicken, it\u2019s important to take steps to minimize the risk of foodborne illness, as undercooked chicken can harbor harmful bacteria like *Salmonella* or *Campylobacter*. Here\u2019s what you should do:\n\n### 1. **Stay Calm and Monitor Symptoms**\n   - Not everyone who eats undercooked chicken will get sick, but it\u2019s important to watch for symptoms of food poisoning. These may include:\n     - Nausea or vomiting\n     - Diarrhea\n     - Abdominal pain or cramps\n     - Fever\n     - Fatigue\n   - Symptoms typically appear within 6\u201372 hours after consumption.\n\n### 2. **Hydrate**\n   - If you experience diarrhea or vomiting, drink plenty of fluids (water, clear broths, or oral rehydration solutions) to prevent dehydration.\n\n### 3. **Rest**\n   - Give your body time to recover by resting and avoiding strenuous activities.\n\n### 4. **Avoid Certain Foods**\n   - Avoid dairy, caffeine, spicy foods, or alcohol until your stomach settles, as these can worsen symptoms.\n\n### 5. **Seek Medical Attention if Necessary**\n   - Contact a healthcare provider if:\n     - Symptoms are severe or persistent (e.g., diarrhea lasting more than 3 days).\n     - You experience a high fever (over 102\u00b0F or 39\u00b0C).\n     - You notice signs of dehydration (e.g., dizziness, dark urine, or reduced urination).\n     - You have a weakened immune system or underlying health condition.\n\n### 6. **Practice Good Hygiene**\n   - Wash your hands thoroughly with soap and water to prevent spreading bacteria to others.\n\n### 7. **Prevent Future Incidents**\n   - Always ensure chicken is cooked to an internal temperature of 165\u00b0F (74\u00b0C) to kill harmful bacteria.\n   - Use a food thermometer to check for doneness.\n   - Practice safe food handling, such as avoiding cross-contamination and storing chicken properly.\n\nMost cases of food poisoning from undercooked chicken are mild and resolve on their own, but it\u2019s important to monitor your health and seek medical advice if symptoms are severe or concerning.",
